I hope, sir, no very dreadful accident is the cause of your coming hither; but, whatever it was, you may be assured it could not be otherwise; for all things happen by an inevitable fatality; and a man can no more resist the impulse of fate than a wheelbarrow can the force of a wheelbarrow driver.”  Besides the obligation which Mr. Robinson had conferred on Mr. Booth in delivering Mr. Booth from the insults of Blear-eyed Moll, there was something in the manner of Mr. Robinson which, notwithstanding the meanness of Mr. Robinson dress, seemed to distinguish Mr. Robinson from the crowd of wretches who swarmed in those regions; and, above all, the sentiments which Mr. Robinson had just declared very nearly coincided with those of Mr. Booth: this gentleman was what those of Mr. Booth call a freethinker; that is to say, a deist, or, perhaps, an atheist; for, though Mr. Robinson did not absolutely deny the existence of a God, yet Mr. Robinson entirely denied Providence.
